<body>
    <header>
        <h1><marquee height="45">Kova Sweet</marquee></h1>
    </header>

    <section>
        <h2>Ingredients</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>2 cups full-fat milk</li>
            <li>1 tablespoon lemon juice or white vinegar</li>
            <li>1/4 cup sugar (adjust to taste)</li>
            <li>1/2 teaspoon cardamom powder</li>
            <li>Chopped nuts for garnish (almonds, pistachios, etc.)</li>
        </ul>
    </section>
    <section>
        <h2>Tags</h2>
        <ol>
            <li>sweet</li>
            <li>dessert</li>
        </ol>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Instructions</h2>
        <ol>
            <li>Boil the full-fat milk in a heavy-bottomed pan. Once it boils, add lemon juice or vinegar to curdle the milk. Stir until the whey separates from the curd.</li>
            <li>Strain the curdled milk using a muslin cloth to obtain chenna (paneer). Discard the whey.</li>
            <li>Now, crumble the chenna with your hands to get a grainy texture (kova). This is also known as khoya.</li>
            <li>Heat a non-stick pan and add the crumbled chenna. Cook on low to medium heat, stirring continuously to prevent burning.</li>
            <li>Add sugar and continue cooking until the kova thickens and leaves the sides of the pan. Add cardamom powder and mix well.</li>
            <li>Remove from heat and let it cool for a few minutes. Shape the kova into small round balls or any desired shape.</li>
            <li>Garnish with chopped nuts and let the kova sweets cool completely before serving.</li>
            <li>Serve and enjoy the delicious Kova Sweet!</li>
        </ol>
    </section>
